{"/service/ndnp/nbu/batch_nbu_junco_ver02/data/2023271005/00542866202/1924052901/0305.xml":{"full_text":"Are you working for your bou or\nworking him?\nThe man who really does big thing*\nti too busy to brag about them.\nToo many children of poor folk*\nnr* being raised like they were rich.\nThe world improves slowly. I\nnotice Bill Maupin Las quit wearing\nynllow shoe*.\nLew Shelley thinks it ought to bo\nagin the law for female book agent*\nto eat onions\nAmong other ways of being modern\nI* swapping a comfortable beating\nstove for a furnace.\nHappenings at Washington show\nthat no one party is large enough to\nhold all the crooks.\nHow much time did you spend\nstudying the good points in your\nlast new photograph?\nThe trouble with most of us la that\nwhen we get out of debt we turn\nright around and go In again.\nSoft Jobs make soft men This coun\ntry needs more men who will tough\n\u00abn themselves with hard work\nA real diplomat I* a man who al\nways remembers a woman's birthday\nbut never knows which one It I*.\nIf a hold-up man ever sticks me up\nand takes my jewelry all he will get\nwill be two 10-cent collar buttons\nSomeone remarks that a righteous\ntown Is one wherft the druggist doesn\u2019t\nknow what you mean when you wink\nat him.\nYoung men should remember that\nthe big question isn\u2019t how to get a\nwife but how to support her after\ngetting her.\nThe ads and stories in popular\nmagazines all teach that there is no\nnecessity for hard work. Us older\nfolks know better\nMore misery is caused by eating too\nmuch than ever was caused by drink\nlog hard licker I*. S. This isn t meant\nas a boost for the wets\nOne of the pleasures of reading th*\nhome town paper is guessing who tbs\neditor is hitting at If he happens M\nsay something original\nIf John Sweet of Nebraska City owes\nyotj anything you had better coilect it\nwhile he is alive. Ho accuses me of\nsmoking Corn Cake tobacco\nIf aome merchants didn\u2019t speak to\ntheir wives any oftener than they ad\nvertise in the home paper they would\nlive on cold mush most of the time\nNo modern boy ever enjoyed the\nezqulsite pleasure of taking a hot\nflatiron to bed with him on a cold\nnight He demands that the whole\nroom be warm.\nWhen you see a man tearing along\nth* road at a high rate of speed the\nchances are he isn\u2019t going any place\ni* particular and haa nothing to do\nafter he gets there\nA tbnfty nuts 1b often abused tor\nnot spending more money on his\nfamily when he ought to be praised\nfar providing for the future as well as\nfar the present.\nNew York City put up $255,000 for\nthe privilege of entertaining the\ndemocrat convention. What Nebraska\ntown wants to put up that much far a\nmeeting of the Nebraska Press As\nsociation?\nla spite of the fact that practically\nall successful men got their start by\ndoing hard work, most young folks\nthink the way to get ahead is by look\ning for soft snaps And (oo many\nparents agree with them\nSomeone remarks that what this\ncountry needs nowadays is not a\nreal job for every man but a real\nman for every Job.\nIf you are square enough to wla\nthe approval of your neighbors you\ndon\u2019t need to worry much about what\nother folks think of you.\nA llartington man says women\nain't no count no more. He says bis\nwife never has to start work before\nfive in the morning but sbe is al\nways all fagged out by nine at night.\nDid you ever stop to think that\nmost of your troubles are your own\nfault?\nSilk may be warm but when It te\nthin enough to show the pink bide un\nderneath. it ia Impossible to make me\nbelieve it is very comfortable.\nI don't uphold the use of tobscce.\nIt is a waste of time and a detriment\nto the health of most people. Rut, at\nthat, I claim it doesn't do as much\nbarm in the world as beefsteak and\nsoft drinks.\nCLIPPINGS FROM EXCHANGES\nGordon Loses Business Territory\nJules A. Sandoz, owner of the fam\nous fruit orchards 40 miles northeast\nof Antioch, returned Tuesday morning\nfrom a trip to Denver. Mr. Sandoz\nsays that the government has estab\nlished a new mail route for all the\ncountry in his neighborhood and be\nginning July 1st, mail will come by\nway of Ellsworth instead of by way\nof Gordon, as at present and in the\npast. As it means the loss of many\nthousands of dollars to businessmen\nof Gordon, he cannot understand why\nthey allow it to slip through their fin\ngers. He talked quite entertainingly\nabout the musk rat industry through\nout the sandhills country, and says\n,hat the rats are multiplying over in\nhis country so rapidly that soon they\nwill become a pest and of serious in\njury to the land necessitating drastic\nmeasures to get rid of them. Dozens\nof them are killed daily by automo\nbiles running over them. They wand\ner away from the lakes, getting in\nthe ruts on the road and do not know\nenough to get out of the way of cars.\nThe reason for this is that the mink\nis the natural foe of the rats. During\nthe past two seasons, mink hides have\nbeen valuable, resulting in the exter\nmiuauon or me mniK, wmcn causes\nthe rats to breed prodigiously. The\nwhole country over there has lived\nand made money from the sale of rat\nskins and it is estimated revenues\nfrom this source have been far in ex\ncess of revenue from the cattle in\ndustry. Mr. Randoz, in addition to\nthe large orchards he now has in bear\ning is setting out this spring twenty\nthousand more fruit trees. His or\nchards have made Sheridan county\nfamous throughout the United States\nand upon the return of prosperity to\nthe agricultural industry immigration\nto Sheridan county will exceed any\nthing known to the Pacific coast coun\ntry, the whole of which is not cap\nable of producing equal to Sheridan\ncounty alone, and certainly there is\nno comparison in flavor of fruits\ngrown.\u2014Alliance News.\nFor the first time in eight years an\naudit Is being made of the accounts\nof Cherry county officers. The firm of\nChas. It. Warren Co., of Lincoln was\nrecently awarded the job by the board\nof county commissioners, for the stat\ned sum of $1050, the audit to cover\nthe years from 1916 to date. The last\naudit was made by the late E. J. Rob\ninson and disclosed nothing particul\narly wrong in the accounts of county\nofficers over a long period. Nothing\nwrong is expected to be developed\nthis time, but the audit is being made\nas a precautionary and business meas\nure. Probably it should be done every\nfour years. The price paid will amount\nto approximately $130 per year for\nthe term covered. D. A. Bay has been\nat work at the books for the last two\nweeks. He is expecting to be Joined\nby two other employees of the firm,\nwho are at present engaged elsewhere.\nWith three men at work it was ex\npected that the job could be complet\ned in about six weeks but with the\ndelay in the arrival of the extra men,\nIt will take longer. The work is being\ndone in the new room in the basement\noccupied by the city library. This\nroom was fitted up for Just such pur\nposes.\u2014Valentine Republican.\nA. it. Modisett, chief brand inspect\nor for Sheridan county, has complet\ned appointment of local Inspectors at\nall shipping points in Sheridan county\nas follows: Bingham, J. R. Edmund\nson; Ellsworth, Walter A. Wightman;\niatkeside, Robt. A. Cook; Antioch,\nChris Jamison; Hay Springs, Wm.\nHolstein; Clinton, Nels Tausan;\nRushville, BenJ. Robins; Gordon, Fred\nC. Duerfeldt. No cattle can be ship\nped from Sheridan county without the\nrailroad agents having first received\ncertificates of brand inspection from\nthe local inspector at the point of\nshipment. The system will be in op\neration in Cherry, Box Butte, Sioux\nand Garden counties shortly Alliance\nNews.\nCONFINE THE NEWLY\nHATCHED POULTS\nEarly brood management of young\nturkeys should be such as will pre\nvent losses, advises the Agricultural\nCollege, Lincoln. For the first few\ndays the hen and her brood, if the\npoults are being reared by natural\nmeans, should be confined to a coop\nor slatted run on clean ground, that\nis, ground which has not been used\niust previously for chickens or grown\nturkeys. This confinement will keep\nthe little turkeys from getting wet in\nthe morning dew.\nFISH CULTURE IN NEBRASKA\n(Continued from Page Three)\ntion of fish?\nThat the following species of fishes\nwere successmully introduced to Ne\nbraska waters through the medium\n'of the fish hatcheries? Brook, trout,\nrainbow trout, brown trout, Loch Lev\nen trout, wall-eyed pike, crappie ring\nperch, rockbass and small mouth\nblack bass.\nThat the first large mouth black\nbass to come to Nebraska was through\nan accident to one of the U. S. fish\ncars in crossing the Elkhorn. A num\nber of bass were being transported\nfrom eastern waters to the west.\nWhen the accident occurred in order\nto save the fish they were deposited\nin the Elkhorn river, stocking this\nstream and its tributaries with bass.\nThat Nebraska owns and operates\nthree fish hatcheries that are propa\ngating and distributing millions of\nfish each year.\nThat the oldest living fish culturist\nin point of years of service in the\nt'nited States, is operating one of\nthese hatcheries.\nThat if the fish now in the lakes in\nCherry county were accessible to all\nthe people of the state, they would\nafford good fishing to the whole of\nthe people and provide a wonderful\nsupply of fish food.\nThat until the bass were winter\nkilled in these lakes nine years ago\nthere were no bass waters in the Un\nited States superior to those in Cher\nry county.\nThe next time you fishing fans feel\nthe lure of the rod and reel or the\n\u201cold fishin\u2019 pole\u201d and you have e\nnougli time to indulge in a real outing\nresolve to give the good old state of\nNebraska a chance to fill your basket.\nCome out to the Sand Hill lakes.\nHere you can get the thrill of pulling\nout a big scroppy bass, the giant\ncrappy, the ring perch or the little\nsunny. I\u00a3 this does not satisfy, the\nspringstreams will furnish you with\ntrout fishing. You will not find ele\ngant hotels, with big easy chairs on\nthe veranda, overlooking miles of\nbeautiful landscape, but you will find\na good plac^p for a real outing, and\nit is doubtful if you will find a better\nfishing ground anywhere than the\nSand Hill lakes of northwest Nebras\nka.\n:tmiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiuinimmi\nU No Gum\nAT THE CRYSTAL BAKERY\nAnd you know the quality of all Crystal Bakery\nProducts.\nPhone 168\nGordon, Nebraska\niiiinimimiiimiiimmmimmiiiiiimiiiiimi\nEvery 20th Subscriber\nIs a Telephone Investor\nNO other business in the\nworld has such wide\nownership of its stock and\nbonds aa the Bell Telephone\nSystem.\nBetween 400.000 and\n500,000 people own Bell Tele\nphone securities. This is one\ninvestor for about every\ntwenty subscribers.\nBell Telephone stock offer*\na profitable, conservative and\nsafe investment. For every\ndollar\u2019s worth of securities\noutstanding, a dollarfias been\ninvested in property of the\nSystem.\nYou. too. can become a tele\nphone stockholder and be a\npartner in this great industry.\nAsk any telephone employee\nabout it.\nThe interests of the public, of our em\nployees and our investors are the same.\nNorthwestern BeliJ\nTelephone Company\npilllllllllllilllllllllllllllllllllllllllllllllllM\nINew Stock!\nOf well supplies now on hand. This will include windmills, pumps, pipes, Cyl-\ninders and fittings.\nMowers and Rakes l\n=j See our new Minnesota No. 2 mowers and rakes on display at the store. |i\nThese just arrived and are worthy of your inspection. Also we have taken\nEE over from the Farmers\u2019 Union a stock of repairs for the Evans and Oliver\nPotato Planters, Massey-Harris and Moline binders, Thomas, Johnson and Mo-\nline mowers.\nWaddill Bros. Heavy Hardware\nSinclair Oils Federal Tires\niiiiiiiiiifiiiiiiiiHiiiiiiiiitmiiiiiiitiiiiiiiiiiimiiiiiiiii\n<iiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiimiiiiiiiiiiiiimiiimiiiiiiiiiiiv:iiimiiiiiiiiiii\nGrocery Headquarters\nThere is not a more complete line of Food Products\nhandled in Gordon than at the Boys\u2019 Store.\nWe Feature\nWONDER\nFLOUR\nI PUTS MAGIC^I\nIN YOUR BAKING\nOmfilia Flour Mrll.f Oi5w.n\u00ab\nEVERY SACK GUARANTEED\n1 RICHELIEU CANNED GOODS\nAre choice goods and their quality is unexcelled. We\ncarry a complete line and will be glad to fill your\nwants.\n1 SEE US FIRST\nI Fritz Brothers\n\n\\i)iib gasoline\nas with paint\nBALANCE\nthat\nCOUNTS\nHIGH quality pigments and oils don\u2019t\nguarantee a paint that spreads, covers\nand wears well. Neither do low, medium and\nhigher boiling point fractions in gasoline as\nsure superior motor fuel. In both cases bal\nanced proportions determine real worth.\nIf altering the proportions of low and higher\nboiling point fractions in Red Crown would im\nprove it, we would change it to a blended gasoline.\nBut Red Crown is so accurately balanced to give\nquick starts in any weather, burns up with such a\nslight residue of carbon, develops power so de\npendably and gives such big mileage per gallon\nthat it would be a mistake to change it.\nInnumerable experiments have proved that you\ncan neither add nor take away any fraction of\nRed Crown and have as good an all-around\nmotor fuel.\nDrive up to any garage or dealer when you see\nthis sign and you are sure of dependable service\nand full measure of gasoline that is uniform and\nproperly balanced for quick starts, power and\neconomy. There you can buy Polarine motor oils\nthat provide protective lubrication.\nWrite or ask, for Red Crown road map\nSTANDARD OIL COMPANY\nOF NEBRASKA\nRed Crown\ncThe Balanced Gasoline\n---;\u20141","height":"26188","width":"19008"}}
